
<item rdf:about='http://www.ietf.org/internet-drafts/draft-farinacci-lisp-rfc6830bis-00.txt'>
    <title>"The Locator/ID Separation Protocol (LISP)", Dino Farinacci, Vince Fuller, David Meyer, Darrel Lewis, Albert Cabellos-Aparicio</title>
    <link>http://www.ietf.org/internet-drafts/draft-farinacci-lisp-rfc6830bis-00.txt</link>
    <description>This document describes the Locator/ID Separation Protocol (LISP) data-plane encapsulation protocol.  LISP defines two namespaces, End- point Identifiers (EIDs) that identify end-hosts and Routing Locators (RLOCs) that identify network attachment points.  With this, LISP effectively separates control from data, and allows routers to create overlay networks.  LISP-capable routers exchange encapsulated packets according to EID-to-RLOC mappings stored in a local map-cache.  The map-cache is populated by the LISP Control-Plane protocol [REF_TO_RFC6833bis].  LISP requires no change to either host protocol stacks or to underlay routers and offers Traffic Engineering, multihoming and mobility, among other features.</description>
    <dc:date>2016-11-13T08:00:00-00:00</dc:date>
</item>
